  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The symptom of a rough idle and stalling, especially requiring throttle input to prevent stalling, is a classic indication of an issue with the idle air/fuel mixture or insufficient idle speed. For a 1965 289 V8 with an Autolite 2100 2bbl carburetor, the most common culprits are either an improperly adjusted idle mixture screw, an incorrect idle speed setting, or a vacuum leak. A vacuum leak introduces unmetered air, leaning out the mixture and causing a rough idle or stall. The provided FSM documents do not contain specific troubleshooting procedures for engine idle issues, carburetor adjustments, or vacuum leak diagnosis. Therefore, the diagnostic approach will follow general best practices for this type of carbureted engine, starting with the most common and easily verifiable causes.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The rough idle and stalling at stop lights indicate a lean condition or insufficient idle speed. We need to address the idle circuit of your Autolite 2100 carburetor or identify a vacuum leak. First, ensure the engine is at normal operating temperature. Then, we will check the basic idle settings. Locate the idle speed screw (which rests against the throttle linkage) and the idle mixture screws (usually one or two, on the front of the carburetor base).",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "When adjusting the idle speed screw, the engine RPM increases significantly, but the rough idle persists.",
    "When adjusting the idle mixture screw(s), turning them in (clockwise) does not cause the engine to stumble or die, and turning them out (counter-clockwise) has little to no effect on idle quality.",
