  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The symptoms of pinging/knocking under acceleration or uphill, running hot, and lacking power are classic indicators of pre-ignition or detonation. For a 1965 289 V8, the most common mechanical causes are incorrect ignition timing (too advanced) or a lean fuel mixture. Both conditions cause the combustion event to occur too early or too rapidly, leading to excessive cylinder pressure, heat, and reduced power. While the provided FSM documents do not contain specific engine diagnostic procedures for these symptoms, the first step in diagnosing such issues on this engine is always to verify the ignition timing. Other potential causes include excessive carbon buildup in the combustion chambers or a malfunctioning cooling system exacerbating the heat issue. I will start with the most direct and easily verifiable mechanical check.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The engine pinging and knocking under load, running hot, and lacking power points directly to a combustion issue, most likely incorrect ignition timing or a lean fuel mixture. For a 1965 289 V8, the first thing to check is the ignition timing. You need to verify the base timing with a timing light. Connect your timing light and tachometer. Start the engine and bring it to normal operating temperature. Disconnect and plug the vacuum advance line to the distributor. Set the idle speed to the specified RPM (typically around 600-700 RPM for a 289 V8 with automatic transmission, but consult a full FSM for exact specification if available). Aim the timing light at the harmonic balancer and observe the timing mark relative to the timing tab. What is the reading?",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "The timing is significantly advanced (e.g., 10 degrees BTDC or more, when specification is less).",
    "The timing is retarded (e.g., 0-2 degrees BTDC).",
    "The timing mark is erratic or jumps around.",
    "The timing is within specification, but the symptoms persist."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

