      "context": "REAR SUSPENSION"
    }
  ],
  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The clunk on acceleration and vibration at speed strongly suggest excessive play or imbalance in a rotating drivetrain component. My primary hypothesis is worn universal joints (U-joints) in the driveshaft. When torque is applied from a stop, slack in a worn U-joint will cause a sudden engagement and a clunk. At speed, an imbalanced or binding U-joint will induce vibration. Other possibilities include excessive backlash in the differential (covered under 'GENERAL AXLE SERVICE' and 'PINION AND RING GEAR TOOTH CONTACT ADJUSTMENT' in the FSM) or loose rear suspension components (like spring clips or bushings, referenced in 'REAR SUSPENSION'). However, U-joints are the most common culprit for both symptoms simultaneously. The FSM does not provide a specific U-joint diagnostic procedure, so a direct physical inspection is the next logical step.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The clunk on acceleration and vibration at speed point to play in the drivetrain. We need to check the driveshaft universal joints (U-joints) first. Raise the vehicle safely on a hoist. With the transmission in neutral, grasp the driveshaft firmly and attempt to rotate it back and forth by hand. Observe the U-joints at both ends of the driveshaft (transmission and differential). Look for any rotational play or looseness in the U-joint crosses or caps. Also, try to move the driveshaft up and down and side to side at each U-joint to detect any vertical or horizontal play. A visual inspection for rust, missing grease, or damaged caps is also critical.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "I found significant rotational play and/or visible looseness in one or both U-joints when manipulating the driveshaft.",
    "The U-joints feel tight with no discernible play, but there is rotational play when rotating the driveshaft, indicating play within the differential itself.",
    "The U-joints feel tight, and there is no significant rotational play in the driveshaft, but I noticed movement in the rear axle housing or leaf springs."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

