  "mechanic_instructions": "The parking brake's inability to hold the car on a hill, even with the handle fully engaged, points to an issue with the parking brake cable, its lever mechanism, or the adjustment of the rear brake shoes. We need to verify the mechanical integrity and adjustment of these components.\n\nFirst, inspect the parking brake lever's contact with the adjusting screw toothed wheel. With the brake in a vertical position (anchor at the top), the lever should contact the adjusting wheel 3/16 inch (plus or minus 1/32 inch) above the centerline of the screw. If the contact point is below this centerline, the lever will not lock on the teeth, and the screw will not be turned as the lever is actuated by the cable. (Source 31)\n\nWhile you're there, check the following (Source 31):\n1.  **Cable End Fittings:** Ensure the cable completely fills or extends slightly beyond the crimped section of the fittings. Damage here indicates replacement.\n2.  **Cable Length:** Measure the cable from the end of the cable anchor to the end of the cable hook. It should be 8 1/8 inches on 6-cylinder models or 10 1/8 inches on 8-cylinder models.\n3.  **Cable Guide:** Verify the cable groove is parallel to the shoe web, and the body of the guide lies flat against the web. Replace if damaged.\n4.  **Pivot Hook:** Check that the pivot hook on the lever has square surfaces for proper pivoting. Replace if damaged.\n5.  **Adjusting Screw Socket:** Confirm the adjusting screw socket is properly seated in the notch in the shoe web.\n\nAfter these checks, if no obvious cable or lever damage is found, the issue is likely the general adjustment of the rear brake shoes. The parking brake system relies on the proper adjustment of the service brakes. You will need to adjust the brakes as detailed in Part 2-2, Section 2 of the FSM (Source 29, Source 37).",
